pageSummary: I am raising money because We want to show thanks for looking after my mum.
pageSummaryWhy: We want to show thanks for looking after my mum.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Myra Macmillan
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my just giving page to help support a fantastic cause in aid of my late mother’s memory. 

My mother Myra sadly passed away on the 23rd of December 2020 after putting up a brave fight against cancer. She found out at the start of lockdown she had bowel cancer and after an operation and 4 rounds of chemo her body just couldn’t carry on. We would love to make a donation to help further unfortunate families battling cancer to get the help and support they deserve and any donation is very much appreciated. I can’t think of a better way of honouring my mother more than helping others as she herself was a very kind and caring woman who would help anyone. All donations go straight to the charity and all your information is safe with the just giving page. 

Thank you all so very much for helping,

pageSummary: I'm hoping to raise much needed funds because I lost a very dear & close friend in October 2020
pageSummaryWhat: I'm hoping to raise much needed funds
pageSummaryWhy: I lost a very dear & close friend in October 2020
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Brione Abbott
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Brione, my dear close close friend of nearly 30 yrs, sadly lost her battle against cancer on the 20th October 2020. 

I had hoped to have run the Chester Marathon at the beginning of October 2020 to raise funds for Macmillan but it was postponed until October 2021 and I never got the chance.

For those of you who didn't know Brione, she was more than just an ex work colleague who I first met in our days of working at Notts County Council Pension Section all those years ago, she was a true friend. Even after I left the council, we stayed in touch and enjoyed many a good evening just talking nonsense whilst drinking (way too much alcohol). She also helped me through some very dark times in my own past as well, especially when I experienced a nasty attack on my way home alone one evening and I had to have the top of my left ear sewn back on. She got me back on my feet and also back out in the world when I was so scared to even venture out of my flat. I just wish I could have done more for her during her painful struggle of this horrible disease.

I've therefore decided to do a virtual challenge of the USA Route 66 in her memory that will culminate in me hopefully crossing the marathon finish line in Chester on Sunday the 3rd October 2021. My virtual challenge starts on the 1st January 2021 and consists of some 2,278 miles that I aim to complete on the 3rd October 2021, meaning I need to run/walk/cycle just over 250 miles a month to ensure when I cross the line in Chester I have completed the entire Route 66 in just over 9 months.

The marathon will only be my second, and I know just how hard they are but with Brione helping me along the 26.2 miles (and also all the training prior to the event) I am sure I will complete this in her memory.  

If you could therefore donate to such a worthy cause I would be eternally grateful. I will be providing a few goodies to be won by folk who kindly donate by asking them to predict my finish time of the marathon and those who come closest to my actual time will win something (Items to be confirmed well in advance of the marathon). For every £5 donated I'll let you have one guess at my finish time - to give you an idea I finished the London Marathon in April 2016 in a time of 4hrs 10 mins 26 secs - however I will be 5 and a bit yrs older with a few extra pounds in weight at the moment too.

Thanks again for taking the time to look at my just giving page and I will keep you all informed of my progress along the Route 66 as often as I can.

Mel

story:

We appreciate your donation no matter how big or small, it will all be going to this amazing cause - THANK YOU!

story:
I will be  doing 1 hour of exercise every day throughout January. This can include walking, running, bike ride or a sweaty home workout.  Every hour of exercise will be tracked on my Strava 🥰 

I have just had to close my hairdressing business for the third time this year and I have a lot of time to kill this month so I want to make it worthwhile.

I chose this charity because Macmillan is a charity extremely close to mine and my family’s hearts after my dad was diagnosed with prostrate cancer in 2019 and now I would like to give something back to say thank you for all the help and support he recieved!

eventName: In memory of Margaret Elizabeth Workman
pageSummary: I am going to complete a monthly challenge because they supported my Grandma's care and the family.
pageSummaryWhat: I am going to complete a monthly challenge
pageSummaryWhy: they supported my Grandma's care and the family.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Margaret Elizabeth Workman
story:
This year I am going to complete a new challenge every month in order to raise donations for Macmillan Cancer Support. The loss of my loved Grandma effected me massively and her memory will never fade, she was the core of our family. This year I have decided I want to give my support to those who helped her when she was in need. 

As you can see below I have not got ideas for the all the months so any suggestions are welcomed and will be considered!

January: Throughout the month run 100KM.
February: Run one 10KM.
March: Walk/Run 100 miles between my parents and I.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: I am cycling in my bedroom because They are fab!
pageSummaryWhat: I am cycling in my bedroom
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Well, hi and thanks for popping over. Lardy here has been as greedy as ever and has not one of the ‘rents supported by Macmillan this year, but both of them!!

Not to be outdone by Mum’s leukaemia, Dad had to wade in with throat cancer. He was incredibly lucky to be seen, diagnosed and treated mid-lockdowns. For that I’ll be forever grateful to the NHS. 

Macmillan have supported the pair of them, even more this past 6 months, and helped where they could with the madness of treatment across a bridge in the midst of a pandemic! 

During his treatment, we as a ‘bubble’ travelled over 2,000 miles back and forth to Castle Hill - I want to replicate that but with the added bonus of saddle sore........... 

You’d be forgiven if fitness wasn’t a word you’d easily associate with me, so I hope you appreciate how hard I’ll be working to prize your pennies from you. And pennies would be great - I know money is tight all over at the minute.

I’ll be logging my rides via Strava and if you want updates on my sore ass then please just ask.

Thanks again and stay safe x

story:
So it’s been a number of years since I was ‘FORCED’ 👀 to retire from football at the tender age of 29, the peak of my powers and since then I have spent some considerable time and effort in perfecting ‘The Dad Bod’. A lot of blood sweat and tears have gone into it and I’m proud of the progress I’ve made but unfortunately I feel now is the time to reign it in a little.

In light of this, I stumbled across this 5km for 10 days challenge by Macmillan and thought what better way to give me the push I need than by raising a little money for a worthy cause. What with 2020 some what overshadowing such severe illnesses with all talk of Covid, I’d like to try and do a little something to help a charity which has suffered along with many others in the last year. I know this isn’t the best time of year, even when not in the midst of a global pandemic but if anyone can spare even a small amount I’d be very grateful.

pageSummaryWhy: they supported my dad through his Cancer treatment
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Brian Jones
story:
My Dad sadly passed away in the early hours of Christmas day as a result of Oesophageal Cancer.

It has been a difficult end to an already difficult year but we will always remember him and how much he loved Christmas and we know he will be looking down on us.

He also talked about giving back to Macmillan, who supported him throughout his treatment. As he never got to do this, and to do something positive in his memory, I have set up this page for anyone who would like to donate.

I would also like to thank everyone for their kind messages and offers of help so far. It has been really comforting.

pageSummary: I'm running every day in January because people with cancer need the Macmillan Support Line
pageSummaryWhat: I'm running every day in January
pageSummaryWhy: people with cancer need the Macmillan Support Line
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
I've been working for Macmillan Cancer Support for over 7 years and never before has the Support Line been more vital.  The Support Line has also evolved over the years to provide advice and guidance on an ever-wider range of issues.  We have people available to provide practical and emotional support, answer clinical questions, provide financial guidance, advise people on work-related issues, provide energy advice and welfare rights advice.  We're facing a funding landscape that is unprecedented, and we're needed more than ever.  I normally keep quite a low profile on social media in relation to my work but we're going to need to get as much support as we can to protect the front-line services Macmillan offers, and keep the charity going in 2021. 

I'm committing to running every day for the month of January, no matter the weather, the temperature or state of mind.  If 100 friends gave me 10p per day, that would be £3.10 each for sticking out the whole month and would raise £310 for Macmillan.  If you can spare that out of your January paycheque, I'd be very grateful, and if you can't, then spreading the word would be just as valuable.  Thank you for your contribution, whether financial or moral support is offered - both gratefully received :)

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support.

I normally do events, Half Marathons, and Triathlons, but don't ask for money for these. This event is different, its on another scale. For this I'm virtually running the length of the country, that's 874 Miles, over 2021, as I said, another level. I ran a reasonable amount in 2020 and did 400miles, so its going to be a big step. 

Our family has a history of heart issues, one way or another and I want to do what I can to make sure it impacts as few people going forward as possible, hence the support for the BHF.  My dad died of a heart attack when he was 48 (and I was 18), and my Grandad (on dads side) died of his second heart attack. Various others have had issues needing bypasses, surgery etc. All of which is too much. 

 The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

Ill be giving updates through the year with progress, hopefully mainly good. ;)


Every Penny and Pound Helps, and please remember to Gift Aid, its free money

eventName: In memory of Jack Joseph Daniel  Speller
pageSummary: I'm passionate about fundraising for because my first son died of a serious heart condition
pageSummaryWhy: my first son died of a serious heart condition
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Jack Joseph Daniel  Speller
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

It's been 21 years since I gave birth to our precious first born son Jack. Unbeknownst to us, he was born with a serious heart condition called Tetralogy of Fallots and at the age of 3 months old became seriously unwell and was fighting for his life. Jack endured immediate heart surgery to correct his heart condition and was responding amazingly well to this life saving surgery but devastatingly lost his life  on 12th August 2001 at the very young and tender age of 7 months old. There's not a day that goes by that we don't miss him and wish he was still here with us. 

In his memory I want to celebrate what should have been his 21st birthday this year by achieving 21km of exercise each week totalling 1,092 km by the end of this year which doesn't seem like much of a challenge but will be one for me! My hope is to reach this target by 16th December and to mark this achievement and Jack's 21st birthday by organising a celebration event of his life (in the hope we're Covid safe by then). Thank you for supporting me in my hope to raise much needed funds for the British Heart Foundation which means so very much to me and my family.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummaryWhat: I am (mostly) running 100 miles in January
pageSummaryWhy: I want to support research into heart diseases
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Duncan Campbell
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation in memory of my Grandpa, Duncan Campbell. 

BHF fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them.

If it wasn’t for this life saving research, our Grandpa might not have had his long life to 90 full of many happy memories with his family. Since the BHF was established the annual number of heart and circulatory deaths in Scotland has fallen by half. 

By supporting BHF you support advances across the spectrum of heart and circulatory diseases; to prevent these conditions from developing and help those with existing conditions to have better, longer lives.

I will be mostly running (but sometimes walking or cycling when my legs need it!) 100 miles over the month of January 2021. As well as fundraising, running really helps my mental and physical health, and became important to me during the first lockdown. Hopefully I’ll be joined by friends & family along the way and it’ll won’t be too gruelling!

Every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit this target,  I'd be so grateful for your support.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
As you may know, Bill Shackman had a severe heart attack on December 8, 2020, while surfing on East Sands in St Andrews, the UK. Thanks to the heroic intervention by fellow surfers and beach bystanders - some with professional medical training - his life was saved and he is now well on the road to recovery. They also benefited from a nearby AED and the prompt response of a local ambulance and its two technicians. 

After he was stabilised at Ninewells Hospital in Dundee, he discovered he had a serious genetic heart condition called XXX. Now that it has been diagnosed it can be managed. 

We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation to support its research into this condition. 

It's only thanks to support from people like you that the BHF can create new treatments and discover cures for conditions such as XXX. Every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Lee Crabtree
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm once again raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be really really grateful for your support to keep Lee’s memory alive.

For the third year in a row myself and a few close friends will be taking on the challenge of the London Winter Walk (COVID permitting) on 27 February 2021. The British Heart Foundation was Lee’s charity of choice and one that he fundraised for a number of times himself by climbing the Great Wall of China and taking on the London to Brighton bike ride more than once (among other things). It continues to be a fitting charity for me to support in his memory given that undiagnosed heart disease was ultimately what took him away from me and our girls so suddenly and at such a young age on 29 September 2018. While we continue to rebuild our lives without him in it, he is never far from our thoughts.  All I can do for Lee now is to try to make him proud every day and to continue the fundraising he started in memory of him so please please do support me if you can. Every little really does help.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. 

Thank you so so much for reading this far and hopefully agreeing to donate to my cause, you will never know how much your support means to me 💙

pageSummary: I am giving up all my favourite snacks in March because I want to raise as much as possible!
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up all my favourite snacks in March
pageSummaryWhy: I want to raise as much as possible!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
The BHF was the chosen charity for donations after Nanny Vi died, so every year I take part in dechox to raise money in her name. 

After a heart related illness in the family struck at the end of 2020, I've never been more determined to try and raise as much as possible. 

That is why this March, I will be giving up chocolate, all sweets, fizzy drinks, cake and crisps. I will also be recruiting family members to give up something they enjoy to raise money in March too- I will edit the post to reflect this as time goes on. 

Ruby-chocolate, sweets, fizzy drinks, cake, crisps

Rachel- Wine and biscuits 

____________________________________________________

Not only The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
eventName: Say Thanks by Donating to Guide Dogs
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story: Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

pageSummary: I’m doing dry January, to raise money because I want to help others through this amazing charity
pageSummaryWhat: I’m doing dry January, to raise money
pageSummaryWhy: I want to help others through this amazing charity
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As many of you know, since 2019 I’ve had a number of surgeries on my eye to save the sight in my right eye. It’s been an emotional and testing time and it’s made me realise how precious our sight is, how much I took it for granted and just how difficult life must be for those living with sight loss. I’m lucky that I still have sight in my right eye, even though it’s not 100%, I am truly blessed. I want to do something to help people who aren’t as lucky as me, so I’m doing dry January to try to raise money for this fantastic cause. I know we’re living in difficult times, and finances are limited, but any donations you can make will help x

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am undertaking a virtual Lands End to John O’Groats  Cycle challenge (1083 miles/1744.2km), in order to get fit and to raise money for Great Ormond Street Children’s Hospital. 

I have until May to complete the challenge but hope to complete it as quickly as I can on a combination of my exercise bike and normal bike. 

If you would like to sponsor me and help me raise money for a good cause I’d be very grateful! 

Thanks

Max

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Our son was born with a rare condition. It was noticed at birth but due to it's rare nature Louie was not diagnosed until he was 6 months old. He was referred to Great Ormond Street Hospital and from that day we can honestly say we are safe hands. At aged 3, Louie underwent a 9 hour operation and this has changed his life forever. We are so pleased with the results and the progress Louie has made and couldn't be more thankful for the fantastic medical care, advise and support we have received from GOSH.

So to do my bit to say a huge thank you this January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in "Running off Christmas". I'll be running 62 miles, doubling the set 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

story:
2020 was a challenging year for everyone, so we wanted to kick of 2021 by doing something positive that will help so many people out there. GOSH is a truly amazing charity, helping thousands of seriously ill children to give them the best chance of fulfilling their best potential. 

We can’t get to get started, and we’ve certainly got our work cut out for us because running 62 miles is 11 times the height of Mount Everest! 

We are extremely grateful for any donations, no matter how big or small to help this fantastic charity! Let’s make a difference! 

Ben & Holly xx

I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!

GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
So I'm doing another charity running event. This time its a total distance over a month. 31 miles in 31 days! 

Since I did the Great North Run I've done pretty much zero activity and during lockdown I have barely moved from either the sofa or my desk (I'm essential apparently). So I've decided to kick-start my plan to get back into some sort of shape that doesn't resemble a potato by running for Great Ormand Street and I was only partly pressured into it by a friend to join their team (check out their pages too!). Yes the team is called 'Mums who run' and no I don't have kids. The team name was chosen before I was peer-pressured whilst in a drunken state on NYE into joining. 

After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most.It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity). 

When I was 16 months old I went to Great Ormond Street Hospital to have a big operation on my brain. This was to help stop the seizures that I was having every day. It worked really well and I have been able to grow up and have fun and do most things that my friends do, although I still have lots of hospital appointments and physio to make me strong but I don’t mind as it all helps me.

For a long time I have wanted to do something to say thank you to Great Ormond Street Hospital for everything they have done for me and my family and so I am taking on their ‘Running Off Christmas’ challenge where I will run a mile a day every day in January. 

I know it is a difficult time for everybody at the moment but if you could sponsor me a little it would be amazing and help even more children like me.

Thank you so much,

love Olivia x

story:
So after a rollercoaster 2020 it was amazing to have our Lyla home for Christmas. This time last year Lyla was on day 12 of 20 on life support (ECMO) before the doctors decided she was fit enough to go through life saving surgery to fit her with a mechanical device that would be a bridge to getting her a heart transplant. At 15 months old, and after such a long period of inactivity, Lyla had to learn to do everything again, from using her diaphragm to breathe, lifting her neck, I mean everything.

Throughout all of this we had an incredible team of doctors, nurses, physios, play specialists, occupational therapists and so many more at great Ormond Street hospital (GOSH) who all helped Lyla not only get through to transplant, but to be in the best shape for after so that she would not only survive but thrive with her new gift.

And how she has. 16 days after her transplant and we were home. Every day she makes such leaps it astounds us both, and today she took her first steps on her own. We now have an energetic and very sassy 2 year old on our hands!

None of this would have been possible without the amazing team at GOSH, so for January I have signed up to run 31 miles in 31 days and would love to raise some money for a charity that has helped to save our daughter's life. After the fun and games of 2020 it's fair to say exercise has slipped down the list of priorities!

Please feel free to share and donate to this amazing charity.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Great Ormond Street hospital does amazing work, every year. The children they look after benefit greatly from their work and commitment to young peoples health. I would know because I'm one of those children! 

The help I received from GOSH still impacts my life today and I want to do what I can to say thanks and help them continue that work for others. So across the whole of this year I plan to (virtually) run the length of the UK (and a little extra Via my family home). 

If youd like and are able to donate to this it would mean loads to me and hopefully will do a good thing for a great place as well.

story: Every day, 619 children and young people from across the UK arrive at GOSH. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support and everyone in Team GOSH taking on the iconic 2021 London Marathon will be helping to give seriously ill children the chance of a better future. For more information about the work GOSH does and to find out where Team GOSH's fundraising will go visit the website: https://www.gosh.org/what-we-do

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit Our JustGiving page.

We have chosen to raise money for Cancer Research UK as it is very close to both of our hearts. We are doing this in loving memory of two special people & also for someone close to us who has beaten it!!!!

Firstly we have chosen to do this In loving memory of an amazing Lady, Glo. Glo was Becky's Nan, who undoubtedly was a massive part of her life growing up. Glo was diagnosed with Breast Cancer at the age of 51, as we all know this is no age! This courageous, beautiful lady whilst dealing with other health issues went on to eventually beat this nasty diagnosis. GO ON GLO!! Sadly although Glo smash breast cancer out the part she later passed away in 2012 of other health conditions. R.I.P Glo/Nan 

Secondly a man who we both loved Uncle Tony. Uncle Tony was extremely funny and lived life to the full despite his numerous health conditions. He would always tell us of how naughty he was growing up and would forever be making us laugh!! Uncle Tony had been diagnosed with Prostate Cancer and fought it for 6 years despite being told he would make it that far!! Sadly Uncle Tony passed away this year. R.I.P Uncle Tony

Last but not least an incredible women that we are both proud to know Theresa Harris. Theresa is Becky's mum's cousin who got diagnosed with Breast Cancer on her 53rd Birthday! What a shock for all! It was her first ever check up and thank God she went! Theresa is one of the moment amazing ladies we know, kind, caring and so much fun to be around. She is an absolute warrior and kicked cancer's butt!! So this is also for you!!

eventName: 500km Swim (Manvers to St Luke's Hospice, Plymouth)
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Maurice Sharrock
story:
Goodbye and Good Riddance to 2020, a truly horrible year for so many of us. The year in which I lost my wonderful Dad to oesophageal cancer. Diagnosed in August 2020 and predicted approximately 2 months to live, we said goodbye only 2 weeks after diagnosis.

A shock to all of us but a fortnight full of golden moments and laughter, caring for him in his last days.

Supported by the wonderful medical teams in Wembury, at Derriford Hospital and by St Luke's Hospice, Plymouth - your compassion, care, information, support and humour was inspirational in a difficult time.

So, to help shift my Lockdown Lard, I am taking on a 2021 Challenge; to swim from my home, via Manvers Lake, to St Luke's Hospice in Plymouth. The route may be virtual but the swims will be real.

311 miles or 500,000m

Yes, that's half a million metres open water swimming and will take me (probably) the whole year (or most of it).

My aim is to raise some money for the charities that have suffered during 2020 and that helped us, so that they can continue their good work helping others.

So this is for St. Luke's Hospice, Plymouth and Cancer Research UK. You can choose which charity to donate to.

Follow my journey on social media or, better yet, come and swim with me for some of the distance (as much as Tiers and Lockdowns will permit).

pageSummary: Katie-Lou, Jack and Myles are running because we want to help kick cancer’s butt!
pageSummaryWhat: Katie-Lou, Jack and Myles are running
pageSummaryWhy: we want to help kick cancer’s butt!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Hello, Katie-Lou, Jack and Myles here, thanks for taking a look at our page. 

We have decided to challenge ourselves this January to get off our bums, get fit, and spend some quality time together in our beautiful surroundings during this next lockdown period. We hope to raise some money for Cancer Research UK whilst doing this, to try and raise awareness and make a difference, however small this new year. 

MUMS MISSION STATEMENT:- Myself and my boys have lost loved ones or still have family members being affected by cancer, and it’s a topic that comes up a lot in our house. “What is cancer?” “What does it do?”  “Why has it taken them away?” “Will we get it?” “Can you stop it?”  I try my best to be honest with the boys and explain my answers in the most appropriate way, but it’s a difficult topic and one that I know brings up uncomfortable feelings and conversations. I thought it would help them deal with things if we could do something positive that would give them a sense of achievement, in honour of our loved ones, past and present. So we decided to run a combined total of 250 miles this January. 

JACKS MISSION STATEMENT:- “I have decided to run 100 miles in January for cancer research because cancer is a horrible thing. My auntie Tina, Grandad Dave and uncle Ste all died from this terrible illness. I really hope I can do this for everyone and raise a lot of money. Jack”

MYLES MISSION STATEMENT:- “Because my Grandad died because he had cancer and I miss him and I am going to run 50 Myles for my Grandad xxx. Myles”

Jack (10) and I (old*) will run 100 miles each (avg. 3.23 miles per day) and Myles (7)  will run 50 miles (avg. 1.61 miles per day). We will mostly be running outside on the roads, but some of our miles will be run indoors on the treadmill due to Rob working and January weather. But miles are miles, no matter where we have run them! :) 

We are hoping to hit a target of £250, that’s a £1 for every mile we run. We hope that you are able to donate, no matter how small, but if you can’t then a like and share will be great so the boys can see the support they have to spur them on. We will be keeping a diary of our runs so people can see our progress and see where we are up to on our targets. See you on the other side xxx

Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Watching the ones you love and care about going through cancer is heartbreaking. pageSummary: I am running 874 miles because I’m slightly mad!
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Cancer is an unforgiving disease, it does not discriminate. It doesn’t matter how healthy, hardworking, kind or selfless a person is, anyone can be affected. It leaves gaping holes in the lives of those it strikes.

I have signed up for the End to End virtual  running challenge which will see me run from Land’s End to John O Groats. I have a year to complete the 874 miles and I aim to run every one! 

When I signed up for my slightly crazy running challenge I didn’t have any thoughts of raising money for charity. Last year has been a hard year for so many people and to ask for money seems a bit cheeky. Reflecting on the people we know who are currently fighting this disease and to those we have lost, I felt that it was right that I should try to hopefully raise a small amount of money to support the future of cancer research and help end the devastating effects of Cancer. 

If you feel you have a little to spare to help me reach my goal of a pound for every mile I run that would be awesome. I know we all get bombarded with requests for various charities so any support is very gratefully received. I’m hoping that seeing the total increase will spur me on to lace up my trainers when it’s cold, wet and dark out there and I’d prefer to be inside with a cup of tea! 

Thank you for taking the time to read this!

story:
2️⃣0️⃣2️⃣1️⃣ - the year I got off my arse and sorted my life out.

Yep, I know that sounds like a classic 'New Year, New Me' we all love to roll our eyes at because we say it every year but never do it. I'm guilty of that too, until now.

I desperately want to get myself in shape in time for our wedding this year, but its not just my figure I want to feel better, it's my headspace too. I've never looked after myself, I've never drank enough water, I've never been mindful of what I eat, I have no energy or enthusiasm to cook so either Nick cooks or I eat rubbish, or even not at all. Sometimes I don't feel worthy of looking after myself because I'm already too far gone. I want to change the way I feel about myself and that starts with my diet and exercise.

I've decided this year I want to take part in various challenges that I can do either from home or round the village, and I thought what better way to see me through till the end than rasing money along the way. There's no backing out this way which will just push my motivation even further.

Instead of lots of small fundraisers I've decided to set up 1 fundraiser for a charity that ultimately means the most to me, Cancer Research. I won't go into it too much but mostly for my Dad who I lost to cancer, and other family and friends too over the years.

The idea is I'll be completing 1 challenge a month for the next 9 months. I've decided to start with an easy one, the 10 Day 5K challenge which I'll probably walk to begin with 🤣 I'll document my challenges too so there's no avoiding it, and what better day to start it than today, the 1st day of the year.

If you'd like to set me a challenge for the months ahead, I'd love to hear your ideas!

Thank you in advance for any donations no matter how big or small 🙏💗

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: 4 best friends raising money because they are amazing and so so needed
pageSummaryWhy: they are amazing and so so needed
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Joseph Logue
story:
We have all been best friends for around 11 years now, meeting whilst serving in the British Military. Some of us have changed career, we are all living in different parts of the UK and our friendships have struggled at times but we are still now and always will be connected with love, mutual appreciation and fond memories. We don't get to see eachother as often as we would like but we are coming together now to try and raise as much money as possible for an amazing, worthy cause.

Last year Ellie's step-dad (Joe) whom we have set up this page in memory of, died from cancer. Joe was diagnosed very abruptly and once they knew that he had cancer the disease quickly took over and Joe did not get very long to live. It was extremely hard for the family especially with the type of year it was in 2020 (Covid-19) but Marie Curie were there to help them through their darkest days.

Last month Ellie managed to raise an amazing £800 for the charity and so we have decided to join her in her quest to raise even more money in Joe's memory. Any money that you can give would be amazing and we will all appreciate it so much! We all have different running abilities and experience but hope that together we can reach our target of 200 miles. It will be tough but with your donations to keep us motivated and our supportive friendships we are hoping we can pull this off. 

Thank you to everyone who takes the time to visit our page and donate.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page - Age to Miles. 

Dad, Grace and I decided we wanted to get fit for 2021. But we wanted a good incentive - and what a better incentive than to raise funds for a charity close to our hearts! 

As a district nurse, I work closely with Marie Curie and find their services of invaluable support to both the patient, family and ourselves. They offer so much and need our support back. 

Our grandmother's on both sides passed away following a battle with cancer and both received care from Marie Curie. We want to thank Marie Curie and give a little something back to them for helping our family through difficult times in our lives. 

So, we have decided to combine our ages, convert them to miles and walk/run or cycle the total by 31st January (I turn 26 on 31st Jan so I will be adding an extra mile that day!). 

Our challenge is 106 miles in 31 days! 

Any donation will be much appreciated. Please feel free to message us about our challenge.

My birthday is in January and in comparison cycling the length of Ireland was a doddle! How will you know I have done it?  You’ll just have to take my word for it but the more that is donated the stronger my resolve becomes! 

I’m doing dry January in honour of my good friend Sam Nelson.  Hopefully we can raise a few quid for Marie Curie who were there for Dad and our family in the most awful period in our family’s life.  If you can spare anything it would be gratefully appreciated and will help Marie Curie continue their fantastic work.  Don’t worry I’ll be zwifting during Jan also so here’s to a good start to 2021. Thanks

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummaryWhy: Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: I made it, I’m 50 on burns day. because My beautiful mum and auntie Anne
pageSummaryWhat: I made it, I’m 50 on burns day.
pageSummaryWhy: My beautiful mum and auntie Anne
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
On the 26th of August 2009 we lost our beautiful mum, Ellen to lung cancer. 8 weeks later on the 25th of October 2009 her baby sister also lost her fight for life to lung cancer. Marie Curie were there for us in our hours of need. 

£160 can give one more family one night of their care and loving support. At a time that is so so precious in the last days and hours of your loved ones life. Please help me in providing this care and support.

Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

rememberedPersonSummary.name: Sheila  Morris
story:
Borneo they said!  My reply when!! How? Will their be snakes, leaches, heights or all of the above? I can't say no there is know way we can stop raising funds everyone should have the same dignified death my Mum had with the care and love of the Marie Curie angels at her bedside. 

So here I am signed up for a 6 day trek in the Borneo jungle in May 2022!! We will trek through mountain forest, rushing streams, rivers and isolated villages.

No hotels or home comforts I will have to do it Bear Grylls style killing our food and sleeping under the stars! The kit list includes leach socks which is concerning. But it's all in aid of the Marie Curie Hospice Bradford. We are very lucky to have a Hospice in our city and they need our help more than ever, with events stopped and collecting banned the lost funds is endless! 

So dig deep and support this amazing charity! 

Thank you for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page I appreciate all your support Adele xxx

eventName: Tindal's Penzance 2.6 Challenge (2.6 Marathons in 47 days)
pageSummary: Hi I'm Mark and I'm running because charities need our support now more than ever
pageSummaryWhat: Hi I'm Mark and I'm running
pageSummaryWhy: charities need our support now more than ever
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Save the UK's Charities and donate as much as you can to my 2.6 challenge!

Many fundraising events  in the UK have been postponed or cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic and essential shops have been closed.  Many charities across the UK have been left struggling to maintain their services, that's why the 2.6 challenge was set up, to throw a lifeline to struggling charities around the world.

Keep our Lifeboats out there saving lives!

Too many people are still drowning, and the boats and ships off our shores still need to be rescued.  Even in the midst of a Global Pandemic, the brave men and women of our lifeboat station at Newly and around the UK still sacrifice their time, their health, their safety and sadly sometimes their lives to keep us safe at sea.  

This great charity needs our support now more than ever so It’s never been more important to come together and show how much we care.

2.6 marathons in 47 days!

Starting on 3rd January I will be running from my home in central Penzance along the sea front and back through town every day for 47 days to complete the 68.12 miles.  That's not a lot for you professional runners but for an out of shape 47 year old, it's a lot for me!

Please give all you can afford and think about how much you'd pay to have someone risk their life WITHOUT BEING PAID to rescue you or your family or friends from an unforgiving ocean in a storm and bring you safely back to shore.

Thank you all for your kind support and if you live in Penzance, give me a wave if you see me puffing and panting around town.  I'll do my best to wave back between gasps for air.


Mark

pageSummary: I am walking the length of Britain
pageSummaryWhat: I am walking the length of Britain
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
So in November I signed up for a virtual walk from Lands End to John O'Groats - for overseas friends that is the length of Britain! It is a 12 month challenge with a total distance of 874 miles (1406km in real language). No cycling allowed - just running (yeh right!) or walking (that's me!)

I started on Nov 23rd and have done 91 miles so far. Need to up the rate a bit as I want to try and finish in 10 months.

Any donations would be awesome ...  I am raising for the WWF. In a time when the world is a bit crazy, conservation is still important and is losing its donations and volunteers.

story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. pageSummary: I am raising money because I want to protect our planet and all the animals
pageSummaryWhy: I want to protect our planet and all the animals
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

My name is Evie Hamilton, I am 11years old and My sister is Ruby and she is 9yrs old. We both love animals so much and we want to help to protect all the animals on our planet. People don’t realise how important it is. Elephants are being killed just for their tusks to be taken by poachers, tigers are being hunted, trees are being cut down and turtles will be extinct in years to come due to rising seas washing out the beaches where they are laying their eggs. People are dumping rubbish and plastic is getting into the oceans. Turtles mistake plastic bags for jelly fish and this is really dangerous for them. WWF are doing amazing work to protect our earth and the animals that live on it. Please donate to support me and my sister Ruby in doing the #BigWinterWander this year. We will be walking on Sunday 24th January from Littlehanpton Pier to Worthing pier, which is a distance of 9.1miles!!

story:
WWF's awesome work helps conserve species, habitats, resources and communities, while tackling climate change, pollution, poaching, and more. Nature is way too good to let humans continue to break it.

Beeswax wraps are fabric soaked in beeswax that can mould around food to keep it as fresh as in cling film. They're perfect for carrying your sandwich in or wrapping up some leftovers in the fridge. It's natural and non-toxic and saves some unecessary plastic. The fabric has been kindly donated by Darn It & Stitch haberdashery so the wraps are all different colours and patterns.

The wraps are sold in packs of 3 (one of each S, M and L; or whatever requests you have). Sizes (in inches) are approximately 7x7, 10x10 and 13x13 (though sizes vary). Packs will sent via Royal Mail to the UK and internationally and should arrive within 1-2 weeks (given delays due to Covid). Standard packs are £7 with all profits going to WWF.

pageSummary: I am running my first ever ultra marathon because our biodiversity needs all the attention and funds
pageSummaryWhat: I am running my first ever ultra marathon
pageSummaryWhy: our biodiversity needs all the attention and funds
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
January 1st, 2021 and I have signed up for my first ever Ultramarathon. 54 kilometres of ups and downs on the Isle of Wight with very limited running experience. Stupid or brave? I'll leave that up to you to decide.

But more to the point...

Anyone that knows me will know that my true passion in life is wildlife and having seen the peril our biodiversity globally is at first hand through my work as a wildlife conservationist, I consider it everyone's duty to step up and make a change. As a result, I have chosen WWF (World Wildlife Fund) as my sponsor for this painful challenge. This money will go straight towards funding the amazing work they do all around the world to protect the vulnerable species and habitats that we all rely on. Little by little we can turn the tide on this crisis and this is my contribution to a better future.

2020 has been a tough year for us all so please don't feel pressured. If you could just give what you can or help me spread the message that would be amazing. 

Thank you all for reading this and PLEASEEE wish me luck because I'm bricking it,

Elliot x

pageSummaryWhat: I am running an ultramarthon of 54K
pageSummaryWhy: Our planet needs action to save our biodiversity.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
My attempt at couch to 5K almost, but not quite completed, I have decided to go from 4.3K to 54k.

I have always been passionate about the environment and have volunteered, donated and even assisted in environmental education in young people. Our planet is the most essential thing that each of us has the privilidge to know and we all need to do our bit to fullfilling a better and richer (nature rich), more diverse future. 

 I am also ridiculously tenacious when it comes to being active and challenging myself in new ways. So when this opportunity arose, my response was almost immediately, YES PLEASE.

Considering I couldn't even run for 3 minutes without stopping, for a whole month of training and after a few months could only run for 30minutes (a great feat to me); this is an incredibely difficult challenge....but what can I say. I live for being active, so let's get this running thing down and added to my list! 

2020

What a year!

I hope that everyone is safe, sane and well & we have a better year ahead!

I understand that it's been a tough year and many people may be in a difficult finacial situation, so please only donate if you feel you are able to! 

1st of January 2021, 

Challenge identified ✔

Raise money for our precious environment ...

charity.description: Oxfam is a global movement of people who won’t live with the injustice of poverty. Together we save lives in disasters. We help people build better lives for themselves. We speak out on the big issues, like inequality and climate change. And we won’t stop until we end poverty for everyone. Join us
charity.name: Oxfam
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk

rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.
